# **Node.js — cheatsheet**

Node JS — is a C++ program. It is a process on a computer.  
Process — is a program in execution.  
Node JS — runs in a Single Thread.  
Thread — is a sequence of instructions  
So all instructions in Node JS runs linearly (one by one) in one thread.

V8 — layer of abstractions to C++ features.  
Google’s V8 engine — converts JS code into \-\> machine code.

libuv — open source library for asynchronous I/O(input/output)  
libuv — implements Event Loop and Thread Pool.

Event Loop — is for easy tasks(callbacks, network).  
Thread pool — is for heavy tasks(file compression, file access).

### **Single Thread phases**

1. Initialize a program

2. Execute “top-level” code

3. Require modules

4. Register event callbacks

5. Start Event Loop provided by libuv

### **Event Loop phases**

1. Expired timers callback nextTick or microtask

2. I/O polling callback nextTick or microtask

3. setImmediate callback nextTick or microtask

4. close callback nextTick or microtask

const fs \= require("fs");  
const crypto \= require("crypto");

const startDate \= Date.now();

process.env.UV\_THREADPOOL\_SIZE \= 7;

setTimeout(() \=\> console.log("2 \- Timer 1 finished"), 0);  
setImmediate(() \=\> console.log("5 \- Immediate 1 finished"), 0);

fs.readFile("./test-file.txt", "utf8", (err, data) \=\> {  
  process.nextTick(() \=\> console.log("4.1 \- Process nextTick"));  
  console.log("3 \- I/O polling task started");

  setTimeout(() \=\> console.log("7 \- Timer 2 finished"), 0);  
  setTimeout(() \=\> console.log("8 \- Timer 3 finished"), 1000);  
  setImmediate(() \=\> console.log("6 \- Immediate 2 finished"), 0);  
  console.log("4 \- I/O polling task finished");

  process.nextTick(() \=\> console.log("4.2 \- Process nextTick"));

  crypto.pbkdf2("password", "salt", 100000, 1024, "sha256", () \=\> {

Stream — is an abstract interface for working with streaming data. Used to process read/write data piece by piece(chunks) without keeping all data in memory.

Streams are instances of EventEmmiter class.

Stream types: 
1. Readable — from them we can read data. (http request) 
2. Writable — we can write the data to them. (http response)
3. Duplex — both readable and writable. (net web socket)
4. Transform — both readable and writable that transform the data. (zlib Gzip creation)

REST — REpresentational State Transfer — is a software architectural style that describes a uniform interface between physically separate components.

REST Principles: 
- separate API into logical resources
- expose structured resource-based URLs
- use HTTP methods(PUT/POST/GET/DELETE) instead new URL
- send data as JSON
- Stateless — all state calculated on the cliend instead of server.

https://xxxxxxxxx.xx/tours  
method: POST      \- to Create/add new tour  
method: GET       \- to Read/get list of tours

https://xxxxxxxxx.xx/tours/${id}  
method: GET       \- to Read/get single of tour  
method: PUT/PATCH \- to Update  
method: DELETE    \- to Delete

If we developing according those principles we are implementing all CRUD operations.
